# The Problem

A form often has many fields (name, email, password). Managing each with a separate `useState` can be repetitive.

```jsx
const [name, setName] = useState('');
const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
```

This is fine for small forms, but for larger forms, consider using a single state object.

Store all form values in one object:

```jsx
const [form, setForm] = useState({
  name: '',
  email: '',
  password: '',
});

const handleChange = (field, value) => {
  setForm({ ...form, [field]: value });
};

// In render
<TextInput
  value={form.name}
  onChangeText={text => handleChange('name', text)}
/>
```

This pattern reduces repetition and makes it easy to add new fields.

## Form Submission

When the user submits the form (e.g., presses a button), gather the data and process it.

```jsx
const handleSubmit = () => {
  // Validate, then send to API
  console.log(form);
};

<Button title="Submit" onPress={handleSubmit} />
```

You can also trigger submit from the last input using `onSubmitEditing` and blurring.
